<h1>6.6 Order of demonstrative and noun</h1>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes-syntactic-relation-labels">Relevant postag
codes / syntactic relation labels</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string</strong>:<br>
See <a href="https://papygreek.com/grammar/47">2.5.3. Demonstrative
pronouns</a></p>
<p><strong>Syntactic label:</strong><br>
Demonstratives are placed directly under the head they modify and are
annotated with the label ATR (ATR_CO if in coordination).</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>ὣς ἄν τις εὕρῃ <strong>τουτω τὸ ὄσστρακον</strong>, δώσι
στρατηρα.<br>
ṑs án tis heúrēi touto tò óstrakon, dṓsi stathra.<br>
<em>Whoever finds this ostracon, will give a coin.</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/10135">o.claud.1.1</a>, 1-3
(sent.1)</p>
<p></p><div style="height:300px; " data-treeid="1" class="sentence-tree tf-tree tf-result" data-json=""><span class="enlarge-button maximize"></span><span class="enlarge-button minimize d-none"></span><div style="height: 100%; width: 100%; overflow: hidden; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);" class="tree-container __________cytoscape_container"><div style="-webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); position: relative; z-index: 0; overflow: hidden; width: 638px; height: 298px;"><canvas data-id="layer0-selectbox" width="1276" height="596" style="user-select: none; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); outline-style: none; position: absolute; z-index: 3; width: 638px; height: 298px;"></canvas><canvas data-id="layer1-drag" width="1276" height="596" style="user-select: none; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); outline-style: none; position: absolute; z-index: 2; width: 638px; height: 298px;"></canvas><canvas data-id="layer2-node" width="1276" height="596" style="user-select: none; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); outline-style: none; position: absolute; z-index: 1; width: 638px; height: 298px;"></canvas></div></div></div><p></p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>Demonstratives can appear both before or after their governing noun,
their position being influenced most likely by pragmatic reasons.
Demonstrative pronouns have predominantly preposed instances;
demonstrative pronominal adjectives are preposed in non-articular NPs
and mostly internal (between the article and the head) in articular
ones. Fixed legal formulae make up a big part of the attested
instances.</p>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<h3 id="annotation-decisions">Annotation decisions</h3>
<p>According to the the AGDT 2 framework <span class="citation" data-cites="celano2014c">(Celano 2014c)</span>, the demonstrative
pronouns should receive the <em>pronoun</em> annotation both when
substantivized and when modifying an NP-head. Demonstrative adjectives,
such as τοιοῦτος (toioûtos), τοιόσδε (toiósde) <em>of such a
kind/quality/nature</em> and τοσοῦτος (tosoûtos), τοσόσδε (tosósde)
<em>of such a size</em> have been annotated in the literary treebanked
corpus predominantly as adjectives. However, due to their pronominal
origin, we have decided to treat them as pronouns in the PapyGreek
corpus, see also <a href="https://papygreek.com/grammar/28">2.5
Pronouns</a>.</p>
<h3 id="ὄδε-οὗτος-ἐκεῖνος">ὄδε, οὗτος, ἐκεῖνος</h3>
<p>As noted already by Mayser (!!ref) and <span class="citation" data-cites="manolessou2000">Manolessou (2000)</span>, there are very few
attributive demonstratives in papyri, so it is difficult to make
generalizations from their distributions. There are only a handful of
instances of ὄδε modifying a noun in our corpus, all but one preposed.
The results for ἐκεῖνος are even fewer and do not allow for a fruitful
investigation. The most common demonstrative in our corpus is οὗτος.
When modifying a noun in an indefinite NP, it is mostly appears in dates
and its usual position after the noun:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>ἔτος τοῦτο ἑνδέκατον<br>
étos toûto endékaton<br>
<em>(during) this eleventh year</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/55768">UPZ.1.24</a>, 3, sent.
1.</li>
</ol>
<p>In definite NPs, οὗτος is equally common before and after the
head:</p>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li>ταυτηνὶ τὴν ἐπιστο|λήν<br>
tautēnì tḕn epistolḗn<br>
<em>this letter</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/31749">p.lond.6.1915</a>, 29, sent.
6.</li>
<li>[τ]ὴν ἐπιστολὴν ταύτην<br>
tḕn epistolḕn taútēn<br>
<em>this letter</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/33022">p.mich.8.476</a>, 20, sent.
11.</li>
</ol>
<p>Fixed formulaic expressions, such as τὸ δὲ δάνειον τοῦτο (tò dè
dáneion toûto <em>this loan</em>), appear again and again in legal
texts. The wide-spread prenominal placement of the demonstrative in
legal formulae, observed by <span class="citation" data-cites="manolessou2000">Manolessou (2000)</span>, p.&nbsp;33, is not as
evident on the scale of our corpus; however, examples of it in
administrative documents can still be found:</p>
<ol start="4" type="1">
<li>τοῦτο τὸ μαρτυροποίημα<br>
toûto tò marturopoíēma<br>
<em>this statement on oath</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/22323">p.babatha.15</a>, l.
12,32</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/75" data-url="search/75">All instances of ὄδε</a></li>
<li><a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/77" data-url="search/77">All instances of οὗτος</a></li>
<li><a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/76" data-url="search/76">All instances of ἐκεῖνος</a></li>
</ul>
<p>The automatically <a href="https://github.com/alekkeersmaekers/duke-nlp/tree/master/xml">Duke-nlp
corpus</a> provides a larger picture, which reveals differences in the
placement distributions of the three demonstrative pronouns. Ὅδε is
overwhelmingly preposed (83% of its attested instances). Οὗτος (which
here, too, is the most common demonstrative) also has a larger number of
pre-nominal instances, but the contrast between the numbers of pre- and
post-nominal attestations is less stark (65% pre- vs.&nbsp;31% postposed),
and there are some internal instances (4%). For ἐκεῖνος, the
predominance of preposed instances is even more diminished (69%
preposed, 5% internal, 36% postposed).</p>
<h3 id="demonstrative-adjectives">Demonstrative adjectives</h3>
<p>In the documents that make up the current PapyGreek corpus, we only
have attestations of τοιοῦτος and τοσοῦτος. They mostly appear in
non-articular NPs in prenominal position, and the majority of instances
come from the UPZ archive:</p>
<ol start="5" type="1">
<li>τοιούτους καιροὺς<br>
toioútous kairoùs<br>
<em>such times</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/55808">UPZ.1.60</a>, 13-14, sent.
3</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/75" data-url="search/75">All instances of τοιοῦτος</a></li>
<li><a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/77" data-url="search/77">All instances of τοσοῦτος</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Within the larger Duke-nlp corpus, demonstrative adjectives are
mostly found before the noun in non-articular and between the article
and the noun in articular NPs.</p>
<h3 id="demonstrative-use-of-αὐτός">Demonstrative use of αὐτός</h3>
<p><span class="citation" data-cites="horrocks2010">Horrocks
(2010)</span> observes that already in texts from the Roman period there
are instances of αὐτός in pre-articular being used in a deictic sense,
due overlapping discourse functions with demonstratives, a phenomenon
which increases in popularity through late antiquity and the Byzantine
period and eventually becomes the standard in Modern Greek (p.&nbsp;128). The
examples of preposed αὐτός in our corpus are too few in order to
corroborrate this, and an interpretation of αὐτός as <em>the same</em>
is still possible:</p>
<ol start="6" type="1">
<li>πέπομφα δέ σοι <strong>αὐτὸ τὸ ἐπίσταλμα</strong> [τὸ]
συ&lt;ν&gt;ηλιγμένον τῇ ἐπιστολῇ ἐπ&lt;ε&gt;ὶ νῦν παρῃτημένοι {σι} τὸν
στρατηγὸν οἱ ὀφείλοντες τὰς μετεπιγραφὰς τὰ&lt;ς&gt; ἕως τῆς ι τοῦ
Μεχείρ·<br>
pépompha dé soi <strong>autò tò epístalma</strong> [tò] synēligménon têi
epistolêi epeì nûn parēitēménoi {si} tòn stratēgòn hoi opheílontes tàs
metepigraphàs tà&lt;s&gt; héōs tês i toû Mecheír.<br>
<em>I have sent you <strong>the commission</strong> wrapped up in the
letter, since those obliged to make conveyance (of their land) by the
10th of Mecheir are petitioning the strategos.</em> (transl. Brashear
2015)<br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1065">BGU.16.2643</a>, 13-17, sent.
4.</li>
</ol>
<p><a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/116" data-url="search/116">See all preposed instances of αὐτός</a></p>
<h3 id="position-of-demonstratives-in-nps-headed-by-a-proper-name">Position
of demonstratives in NPs headed by a proper name</h3>
<p>According to <span class="citation" data-cites="devinestephens2000">(<strong>devinestephens2000?</strong>)</span>,
the frequent postposition of demonstratives with proper names in
literary texts is due to their deictive function with such heads; if the
demonstrative is used restrictively, they appear in the focus position
before the noun. However, there are no instances of demonstratives
modifying proper names in the PapyGreek corpus, and examples from the
automatically annotated Duke-nlp corpus do not corroborate an increased
tendency for postposing the demonstrative in such phrases, compared to
their placement in phrases governed by common nouns.</p>
